{"article_id":"jptECIKIVRTgZ4Li","edus":[{"id":0,"text":"U.S. Coronavirus Testing Still Falls Short .","depth":2},{"id":1,"text":"How 's Your State Doing ?","depth":2},{"id":2,"text":"To safely phase out social distancing measures ,","depth":6},{"id":3,"text":"the U.S. needs more diagnostic testing for the coronavirus ,","depth":6},{"id":4,"text":"experts say .","depth":5},{"id":5,"text":"But how much more ?","depth":4},{"id":6,"text":"The Trump administration said on April 27","depth":8},{"id":7,"text":"that the U.S. will soon have enough capacity","depth":9},{"id":8,"text":"to conduct double the current amount of testing for active infections .","depth":9},{"id":9,"text":"The country has done nearly 248,000 tests daily on average in the past seven days ,","depth":9},{"id":10,"text":"according to the nonprofit COVID Tracking Project .","depth":9},{"id":11,"text":"Doubling that would mean doing about 496,000 a day .","depth":8},{"id":12,"text":"Will that be enough ?","depth":6},{"id":13,"text":"What benchmark should states try to hit ?","depth":6},{"id":14,"text":"One prominent research group , Harvard 's Global Health Institute , proposes","depth":12},{"id":15,"text":"that the U.S. should be doing more than 900,000 tests per day as a country .","depth":12},{"id":16,"text":"This projection ,","depth":13},{"id":17,"text":"released Thursday ,","depth":13},{"id":18,"text":"is a big jump from its earlier projection of testing need ,","depth":13},{"id":19,"text":"which had been between 500,000 and 600,000 daily .","depth":13},{"id":20,"text":"Harvard 's testing estimate increased ,","depth":13},{"id":21,"text":"says Ashish Jha , director of the Global Health Institute ,","depth":13},{"id":22,"text":"because the latest modeling shows","depth":13},{"id":23,"text":"that the outbreak in the United States is worse","depth":14},{"id":24,"text":"than projected earlier .","depth":14},{"id":25,"text":"`` Just in the last few weeks , all of the models have converged on many more people","depth":14},{"id":26,"text":"getting infected","depth":14},{"id":27,"text":"and many more people","depth":14},{"id":28,"text":"[ dying ] , ''","depth":14},{"id":29,"text":"he says .","depth":12},{"id":30,"text":"But each state 's specific need for testing varies","depth":12},{"id":31,"text":"depending on the size of its outbreak ,","depth":12},{"id":32,"text":"explains Jha .","depth":11},{"id":33,"text":"The bigger the outbreak ,","depth":11},{"id":34,"text":"the more testing is needed .","depth":11},{"id":35,"text":"On Thursday , Jha 's group at Harvard published a simulation","depth":11},{"id":36,"text":"that estimates the amount of testing","depth":12},{"id":37,"text":"needed in each state by May 15 .","depth":12},{"id":38,"text":"In the graphic below , we compare these estimates with the average numbers of daily tests","depth":11},{"id":39,"text":"states are currently doing .","depth":11},{"id":40,"text":"To make their state-by-state estimates ,","depth":13},{"id":41,"text":"the Harvard Global Health Institute group started from a model of future case counts .","depth":13},{"id":42,"text":"It calculated","depth":14},{"id":43,"text":"how much testing would be needed for a state","depth":14},{"id":44,"text":"to test all infected people and any close contacts","depth":14},{"id":45,"text":"they may have exposed to the virus .","depth":14},{"id":46,"text":"( The simulation estimates testing 10 contacts on average . )","depth":11},{"id":47,"text":"`` Testing is outbreak control 101 ,","depth":13},{"id":48,"text":"because what testing lets you do is figure out who 's infected and who 's not , ''","depth":14},{"id":49,"text":"Jha says .","depth":14},{"id":50,"text":"`` And that lets you separate out the infected people from the noninfected people","depth":13},{"id":51,"text":"and bring the disease under control . ''","depth":13},{"id":52,"text":"This approach is how communities can prevent outbreaks from flaring up .","depth":12},{"id":53,"text":"First , test all symptomatic people ,","depth":13},{"id":54,"text":"then reach out to their close contacts","depth":15},{"id":55,"text":"and test them ,","depth":15},{"id":56,"text":"and finally ask those","depth":16},{"id":57,"text":"who are infected or exposed","depth":16},{"id":58,"text":"to isolate themselves .","depth":15},{"id":59,"text":"Our chart also shows another testing benchmark for each state :","depth":9},{"id":60,"text":"the ratio of tests","depth":11},{"id":61,"text":"conducted","depth":11},{"id":62,"text":"that come back positive .","depth":10},{"id":63,"text":"Communities","depth":12},{"id":64,"text":"that see about 10 % or fewer positives among their test results","depth":12},{"id":65,"text":"are probably testing enough ,","depth":11},{"id":66,"text":"the World Health Organization advises .","depth":10},{"id":67,"text":"If the rate is higher ,","depth":10},{"id":68,"text":"they 're likely missing a lot of active infections .","depth":10},{"id":69,"text":"What is apparent from the data","depth":7},{"id":70,"text":"we present below","depth":7},{"id":71,"text":"is that many states are far from both the Harvard estimates and the 10 % positive benchmark .","depth":6},{"id":72,"text":"Just nine states are near or have exceeded the testing minimums","depth":8},{"id":73,"text":"estimated by Harvard ;","depth":8},{"id":74,"text":"they are mostly larger , less populous states :","depth":8},{"id":75,"text":"Alaska , Hawaii , Montana , North Dakota , Oregon , Tennessee , Utah , West Virginia and Wyoming .","depth":8},{"id":76,"text":"Several states with large outbreaks","depth":9},{"id":77,"text":"- New York , Massachusetts and Connecticut , among others -","depth":9},{"id":78,"text":"are very far from the minimum testing target .","depth":8},{"id":79,"text":"Some states","depth":9},{"id":80,"text":"that are already relaxing their social distancing restrictions , such as Georgia , Texas and Colorado ,","depth":9},{"id":81,"text":"are far from the target too .","depth":8},{"id":82,"text":"Researchers at the Global Health Initiative at Harvard considered three different models of the U.S. coronavirus outbreak as a starting point for their testing estimates .","depth":5},{"id":83,"text":"They found","depth":6},{"id":84,"text":"that","depth":7},{"id":85,"text":"while there was significant variation in the projections of outbreak sizes ,","depth":9},{"id":86,"text":"all of the models tend to point in the same direction ,","depth":9},{"id":87,"text":"i.e. ,","depth":9},{"id":88,"text":"if one model showed","depth":11},{"id":89,"text":"that a state needed significantly more testing ,","depth":11},{"id":90,"text":"the others generally did too .","depth":10},{"id":91,"text":"The model","depth":8},{"id":92,"text":"they used","depth":9},{"id":93,"text":"to create these estimates","depth":9},{"id":94,"text":"is the Youyang Gu COVID-19 Forecasts ,","depth":7},{"id":95,"text":"which","depth":8},{"id":96,"text":"they say","depth":8},{"id":97,"text":"has tracked closely with what 's actually happened on the ground .","depth":7},{"id":98,"text":"Still ,","depth":7},{"id":99,"text":"the researchers caution ,","depth":7},{"id":100,"text":"these numbers are not meant to be taken literally","depth":7},{"id":101,"text":"but as a guide .","depth":7},{"id":102,"text":"The Harvard testing estimates are built on a model","depth":6},{"id":103,"text":"that assumes","depth":7},{"id":104,"text":"that states continue social distancing through May 15 .","depth":7},{"id":105,"text":"And about half of states have already started lifting some of those .","depth":5},{"id":106,"text":"Jha says","depth":7},{"id":107,"text":"that","depth":8},{"id":108,"text":"without the right measures in place","depth":10},{"id":109,"text":"to contain spread ,","depth":10},{"id":110,"text":"easing up could quickly lead to new cases .","depth":9},{"id":111,"text":"`` The moment you relax ,","depth":9},{"id":112,"text":"the number of cases will start climbing .","depth":9},{"id":113,"text":"And therefore , the number of tests","depth":10},{"id":114,"text":"you need","depth":11},{"id":115,"text":"to keep your society , your state from having large outbreaks","depth":11},{"id":116,"text":"will also start climbing , ''","depth":9},{"id":117,"text":"warns Jha .","depth":7},{"id":118,"text":"A community ca n't base the decision","depth":8},{"id":119,"text":"that it 's safe to open up","depth":8},{"id":120,"text":"on testing data alone .","depth":7},{"id":121,"text":"States should also see a consistent decline in the number of cases , of two weeks at least ,","depth":9},{"id":122,"text":"according to White House guidance .","depth":9},{"id":123,"text":"If their cases are instead increasing ,","depth":9},{"id":124,"text":"they should assume","depth":10},{"id":125,"text":"the number of tests","depth":12},{"id":126,"text":"they need","depth":12},{"id":127,"text":"will increase too .","depth":11},{"id":128,"text":"And ,","depth":11},{"id":129,"text":"Jha warns ,","depth":12},{"id":130,"text":"testing is step one ,","depth":12},{"id":131,"text":"but it wo n't contain an outbreak by itself .","depth":10},{"id":132,"text":"It needs to be part of `` a much broader set of strategies and plans","depth":10},{"id":133,"text":"the states need to have in place ''","depth":11},{"id":134,"text":"when they begin to reopen .","depth":11},{"id":135,"text":"In fact , his group 's model is built on the assumption","depth":13},{"id":136,"text":"that states are doing contact tracing","depth":14},{"id":137,"text":"and have plans","depth":15},{"id":138,"text":"to support isolation for infected or exposed people .","depth":15},{"id":139,"text":"`` I do n't want anybody to just look at the number","depth":15},{"id":140,"text":"and say ,","depth":17},{"id":141,"text":"we meet it","depth":17},{"id":142,"text":"and we 're good to go , ''","depth":16},{"id":143,"text":"he says .","depth":14},{"id":144,"text":"`` What this really is , is testing capacity in the context","depth":15},{"id":145,"text":"of having a really effective workforce of contact tracers . ''","depth":15},{"id":146,"text":"States","depth":16},{"id":147,"text":"that have reached the estimated target","depth":16},{"id":148,"text":"should think of that as a starting point .","depth":15},{"id":149,"text":"`` We 've always built these as the floor , the bare minimum , ''","depth":12},{"id":150,"text":"Jha says .","depth":12},{"id":151,"text":"More testing would be even better ,","depth":12},{"id":152,"text":"allowing states to more rapidly tamp down case surges .","depth":12},{"id":153,"text":"In fact , other experts have proposed","depth":13},{"id":154,"text":"that the U.S. do even more testing .","depth":13},{"id":155,"text":"Paul Romer , a professor of economics at New York University , proposed in a recent white paper","depth":13},{"id":156,"text":"that","depth":14},{"id":157,"text":"if the U.S. tested every resident , every two weeks ,","depth":16},{"id":158,"text":"isolating those","depth":17},{"id":159,"text":"who test positive ,","depth":17},{"id":160,"text":"it could stop the pandemic in its tracks .","depth":15},{"id":161,"text":"Jha warns","depth":11},{"id":162,"text":"that","depth":12},{"id":163,"text":"without sufficient testing , and the infrastructure in place","depth":14},{"id":164,"text":"to trace and isolate contacts ,","depth":14},{"id":165,"text":"there 's a real risk","depth":14},{"id":166,"text":"that states","depth":16},{"id":167,"text":"- even those with few cases now -","depth":16},{"id":168,"text":"will see new large outbreaks .","depth":15},{"id":169,"text":"`` I think","depth":12},{"id":170,"text":"what people have to remember is that the virus is n't gone .","depth":13},{"id":171,"text":"The disease is n't gone .","depth":14},{"id":172,"text":"And it 's going to be with us for a while , ''","depth":14},{"id":173,"text":"he says .","depth":11}],"relations":[{"parent":347,"left":175,"right":346,"relation":"organization","nuclearity":"SN"},{"parent":175,"left":